                    <floruit source="#bib1174-1" notBefore="0300" syriaca-computed-start="0300" notAfter="0399" syriaca-computed-end="0399">300-399</floruit>
                    <note>Fiey provides the following bibliographic citations: <quote source="#bib1174-1">La legende de Benjamin a ete publiee en syriaque et traduite en fraw;ais par Scheil,
"Mar Benjamin", 64-96 ; BHO, 178, 179.
BS, II, 1222- 24 (J.-M. Sauget).</quote>
                    </note>
                    <note type="abstract" xml:id="abstract-en-1174">In hagiography: Benjamin was a disciple
            of <persName ref="http://syriaca.org/person/356">Mar Awgin</persName>. He travelled
            to <placeName ref="http://syriaca.org/place/100">Mount Izla</placeName> and founded a
                        monastery and school near <placeName ref="http://syriaca.org/place/130">Mardin</placeName>. His vita may be a version of the life of Mar <persName ref="http://syriaca.org/person/1379">Miha</persName>.</note>
                    <bibl xml:id="bib1174-1">
                        <title level="m" xml:lang="fr">Saints Syriaques</title>
                        <title level="a" xml:lang="fr">BENJAMIN</title>
                        <ptr target="http://syriaca.org/bibl/650"/>
                        <citedRange unit="entry">89</citedRange>
                    </bibl>
                    <bibl xml:id="bib1174-3">
                        <note>The legend of Benjamin was published in Syriac and translated into French by Scheil.</note>
                        <title>Mar Benjamin</title>
                        <ptr target="http://syriaca.org/bibl/1366"/>
                        <citedRange>64-96</citedRange>
                    </bibl>
                    <bibl xml:id="bib1174-4">
